Men and their hypocrisy.

In The Great Indian Kitchen, the harsh reality of patriarchy is laid bare. Every time the camera shifts to a female character, she is seen in the kitchen, tirelessly preparing food while the men in the house remain detached from the effort. These men are shown lounging around, scrolling through videos on their phones, completely immersed in their own worlds, seemingly unaware or indifferent to the work being done around them.

The most glaring hypocrisy, however, is how they eat. When they sit at the dining table, they consume their food without a second thought for the mess they leave behind. Crumbs and food waste are scattered all over the table, yet the men have no intention of cleaning up. They walk away, leaving the women to do the dirty work. The camera lingers on the aftermath, capturing the unspoken expectation that women will bear the burden of cleaning up, without so much as a thank you.

But the hypocrisy doesnât end there. When these same men step outside the house, they suddenly transform. At restaurants or in public spaces, they eat neatly, use napkins, and make sure they donât leave a trace of their meal behind. They conform to social norms, maintaining cleanliness and etiquette when others are watching. Yet, within the confines of their own home, where women bear the brunt of domestic labor, the standard drops. They indulge in their privilege, showing no respect for the women who clean up after them.

The film captures these moments beautifully, especially the scenes in the kitchen. The camera zooms in on the food being prepared, making you imagine just how delicious it must taste. But as the focus shifts to the women, who are working tirelessly to create these meals, the beauty of the shots becomes haunting. Their faces tell the story of invisible labor.

Mutton Pickle | non veg Pickle |Soul Of Sumi
The non -veg pickle is totally mouth-watering and Indians love pickles  the most and so do . The dish does not require too many ingredients and is a spicy dish and spicy flavor can be adjusted according to our needs pairs up amazingly well with curd rice and plain rice too Mutton pickle simply tastes amazing and irresistible.

Ingredients 
Mutton 1/2 kg (bone less ) 
Ginger garlic paste 1 tbsp 
Turmeric powder  1 tsp 

Pickle masala powder 
Mustard seeds 2 tbsp 
Fenugreek seeds 2 tablespoons 
Cumin seeds 2 tablespoons 

Tempering 
Seasame oil 
Curry leaves 
Dry chilli 
Juice of 2 lemons 
Mustard seeds 
Red chilli powder 1 tbsp
